# Review / Proofread Text
 
Produce an interactive proofreading markup of a piece of writing. The output is a single
self-contained HTML artifact where every flagged passage is highlighted in the text, and
clicking a highlight pops its comment open inline, directly beneath that line. This keeps
each criticism anchored to the exact words it refers to, which is far easier to act on
than a disconnected list.
 
The interaction the user values most: **clicking a highlight reveals the note in place,
with no jumping to the bottom of the page.** The bundled template already implements this.
Do not rebuild it from scratch and do not change the engine.
 
## Workflow
 
1. **Get the text.** It may be pasted in the message, in an uploaded file, or in a Google
   Doc. If it is a `.docx`/`.pdf`/Google Doc, read it first with the appropriate tool. If
   nothing is attached but the user clearly expects a document, ask for it before proceeding.
2. **Read it critically, twice.** First pass for correctness (facts, names, numbers, logic),
   second pass for language (grammar, clarity, consistency, tone). Read the whole thing before
   writing any comments so you catch repetition, contradictions, and naming drift across the
   document.
3. **Verify factual claims. This is not optional.** Any statistic, dated fact, named figure,
   market size, citation, or "X is the largest/first/only" claim gets checked with `web_search`
   before you label it. Cite the primary source in the comment. Do not flag a number as wrong
   from memory: search, then judge. If you previously flagged something and the user supplies a
   source proving you wrong, own it plainly and correct the markup. A confident wrong correction
   is worse than no correction.
4. **Categorise every issue by severity** (rubric below) and decide the fix. Each comment names
   the problem and gives a concrete correction, not just "reword this".
5. **Build the artifact** from `assets/template.html`. Copy it to the output directory, fill the
   four `>>> FILL <<<` zones, wrap each flagged passage, write the matching comments, set the
   scorebar counts. Delete the example highlight/comment block.
6. **Save to the outputs directory and present it.** Then give a short chat summary: lead with the
   critical items, in plain language, and offer to hand back a clean corrected copy with all fixes
   applied.
## Severity rubric
 
Be balanced. A wall of red is demoralising and less useful than a triaged one. Most documents
have only a handful of true criticals. Always include at least one `Verified` item when you have
checked something that holds up, so the review reads as fair rather than hostile.
 
| Class  | Tag      | Colour | Use for |
|--------|----------|--------|---------|
| `crit` | Critical | red    | Wrong facts, broken or unsupported claims, wrong names, anything that would embarrass the author or mislead the reader if sent. Fix before sending. |
| `high` | Fix      | amber  | Clear grammar, spelling, or clarity errors. Unambiguously wrong, but not factually dangerous. |
| `med`  | Style    | blue   | Consistency, word choice, tone, repetition, hyphenation, naming drift. Improvements, not errors. |
| `note` | Note     | grey   | Judgement calls, strategic suggestions, open placeholders, "consider whether". The author may reasonably disagree. |
| `ok`   | Verified | green  | A claim or figure you checked that is correct. Say what you verified it against. |
 
## Comment style
 
Each comment has three parts (Verified items can skip the fix):
- `.snip` — the exact quoted passage, so the user recognises it instantly.
- `.issue` — what is wrong and *why it matters*, in one or two sentences. Explain the reasoning,
  do not just assert.
- `.fix` — the concrete correction. Put suggested replacement wording in `<code>` style so it
  stands out.
Keep comments tight. Quote sparingly and never reproduce long passages of the user's text inside a
comment. Honour any standing writing preferences the user has (for example, a preference against
em-dashes): apply them to your suggested rewrites, and flag violations in their own text as `med`.
 
## Markup conventions (the engine depends on these)
 
A flagged passage in the document column:
 
```html
<a class="hl SEV" data-c="N"><span id="dN">the exact flagged words<sup>N</sup></span></a>
```
 
Its matching comment in the rail:
 
```html
<div class="cmt SEV" id="cN" data-target="dN">
  <div class="cmt-head"><span class="badge SEV">N</span><span class="tag SEV">LABEL</span></div>
  <p class="snip">"the exact flagged words"</p>
  <p class="issue">What is wrong and why.</p>
  <p class="fix"><b>Fix:</b> the correction, with <code>suggested wording</code>.</p>
</div>
```
 
Rules that must hold or the interaction breaks:
- `SEV` is one of `crit | high | med | note | ok`. `LABEL` follows the rubric mapping
  (crit→Critical, high→Fix, med→Style, note→Note, ok→Verified). The `data-c`, the `id="dN"`,
  the `<sup>N</sup>`, and the comment's `id="cN"` / `data-target="dN"` all share the same number `N`.
- Every `N` is unique across the document. Number in reading order.
- For `ok` items you may use `<sup>✓</sup>` and `<span class="badge ok">✓</span>` instead of the number, but keep `data-c`/`id` numeric and matching.
- Never put an `id` attribute inside `.snip`, `.issue`, or `.fix`. The script clones a comment's
  inner HTML when popping it open inline, and a duplicated id would collide.
- Set the five scorebar `<b>` counts (crit/high/med/note/ok) to match what you wrote. The `Comments · N` heading and the Resolved tally fill in automatically, leave them alone.
Structure the document column with `<h2>` for major sections and `<p>` for prose, mirroring the
source. For form-like inputs use `<p class="meta">` with `<span class="field-label">`. Leftover
placeholders in the source can be shown with `<span class="ph">[FILL IN]</span>`.
 
## Built-in reader controls (no markup needed)
 
The engine adds these automatically; you author no markup for them:
- **Resolve.** Every comment gets a Resolve button. Clicking it fades the comment and its
  highlight, flips the button to Resolved, and increments the Resolved tally in the scorebar.
  Clicking again reopens it. This lets the user clear items they judge already addressed as they
  work through the review, in the rail or in the popped-open inline card.
- **Hide resolved.** A toggle in the rail header hides resolved comments so only open ones remain.
- **Live counts.** The `Comments · N` heading and the Resolved count are computed on load, so you
  never hand-count them.
Resolve state is in memory for the session and resets on a full reload; that is expected. Do not
add localStorage or sessionStorage, they are blocked in this artifact environment.
 
## Optional fact-check card
 
When the text leans on several numbers, add the `.statcard` table (commented out at the bottom of
the template) to the rail. It gives a side-by-side of claim vs source vs status. Set the header
green (`style="background:var(--ok)"`) when everything checks out, red when something does not.
This satisfies the common preference to see numbers laid out rather than buried in prose.
 
## Pitfalls
 
- Do not escape into rebuilding the CSS/JS. Fill the template; the engine is the reusable part.
- Read the whole document before commenting, or you will miss cross-references and repetition.
- Search before judging facts. Re-check your own earlier flags if challenged.
- Match every `data-c` to exactly one `id="cN"`. A mismatch leaves a highlight that does nothing.
